{"key":"post-15289870","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15289870</id>\n<content>Your blower is way too powerful.&amp;nbsp; A bic lighter flame should bend over 45 to 60 degrees when held against the face of the filter.&amp;nbsp; It should not flicker or go out, and it should bend the same amount, regardless of where you're holding it on the face of the filter.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You need to stack a couple of prefilters on the intake and see how much that slows down the flow.&amp;nbsp; If it's still too much, block off part of the intake to restrict air being supplied to the blower.&amp;nbsp; I suggest a much smaller blower.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't attempt to test your filter with petri dishes.&amp;nbsp; Never have one open more than a few seconds.&amp;nbsp; Many people will suggest this as a way to 'test' a flowhood, but it's not valid.&amp;nbsp; A good flowhood will have 99.99% efficiency, but that means when there's a few billion contaminant spores floating around the air, many thousands are still going to get through and it only takes one to ruin your day.&amp;nbsp; Always work fast and try to never have an agar plate open for more than five seconds.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15291056</next>\n<prev>15289867</prev>\n<first>15289852</first>\n<last>15291056</last>\n<when>1319809802</when>\n<utime>10/28/11 04:50 PM</utime>\n</post>"}